  ],
  "text": "The LibreOffice document model architecture is built on a hierarchical class structure. The core framework begins with SfxApplication (include/sfx2/app.hxx:103), which represents the main LibreOffice application instance and serves as the entry point for the entire framework. SfxApplication is derived from SfxShell and manages the overall application lifecycle, dispatching, and document management. Below this is SfxObjectShell (include/sfx2/objsh.hxx:182), the abstract base class for all document shells. Every document type (Writer, Calc, Impress/Draw) inherits from SfxObjectShell, which provides common document functionality including printing, saving, loading, and UNO integration. The three main document model classes are: SwDoc (sw/inc/doc.hxx:196) for Writer documents, which represents the core document model with nodes, formatting, styles, and content management; ScDocument (sc/inc/document.hxx:331) for Calc spreadsheets, which manages cells, sheets, formulas, and calculation; and SdDrawDocument (sd/inc/drawdoc.hxx:338) for Impress/Draw presentations, which extends FmFormModel to manage draw pages, shapes, and presentation-specific features. These document classes work in conjunction with their respective shell classes (SwDocShell, ScDocShell, SdDrawDocShell) which inherit from SfxObjectShell and provide the UI integration layer. The architecture follows a clear separation between the document model (data and logic) and the shell (UI and framework integration)."
}

